<subSubSection lastPageId="29" lastPageNumber="180" pageId="28" pageNumber="179" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="28.[151,1436,1719,2033]" lastBlockId="29.[151,1437,151,501]" lastPageId="29" lastPageNumber="180" pageId="28" pageNumber="179">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1719,1745]" pageId="28" pageNumber="179">Remarks.</emphasis>
The genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Meyrick, 1931" authorityName="Meyrick" authorityYear="1931" box="[446,746,1719,1745]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" genus="Merocrates" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="179" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[446,574,1719,1744]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="179">Merocrates</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Meyrick, E." box="[581,746,1719,1745]" pageId="28" pageNumber="179" pagination="33 - 64" refId="ref23699" refString="Meyrick, E. (1931) s. n. Exotic Microlepidoptera, 4 (2), 33 - 64." type="journal article" year="1931">Meyrick, 1931</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
was originally described in the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stainton" authorityYear="1854" box="[1106,1240,1719,1745]" class="Insecta" family="Gelechiidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="179" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Gelechiidae</taxonomicName>
(“Gelechiadae”), but was transferred to the 
<taxonomicName box="[444,610,1755,1781]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="179" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Lecithoceridae</taxonomicName>
(“ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Clarke" authorityYear="1955" box="[635,759,1755,1782]" class="Insecta" family="Timyridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="179" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Timyridae</taxonomicName>
”) by 
<bibRefCitation author="Clarke, J. F. G." box="[819,1024,1754,1781]" pageId="28" pageNumber="179" refId="ref22457" refString="Clarke, J. F. G. (1955 a) Catalogue of the type specimens of Microlepidoptera in the British Museum (Natural History) described by Edward Meyrick. Vol. 1. Trustees of the British Museum, London, 332 pp." type="book" year="1955">Clarke (1955a: 20</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Clarke, J. F. G." box="[1036,1153,1754,1781]" pageId="28" pageNumber="179" refId="ref22557" refString="Clarke, J. F. G. (1965) Catalogue of the type specimens of Microlepidoptera in the British Museum (Natural History) described by Edward Meyrick. Vol. 5. Timyridae, Hyponomeutidae, Ethmiidae, Metachandidae, Cosmopterigidae, Walshiidae, Blastodacnidae, Scythridae. Trustees of the British Museum (Natural History), London, 581 pp." type="book" year="1965">1965: 179</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Gozmany, L." box="[1173,1364,1755,1781]" pageId="28" pageNumber="179" pagination="1 - 306" refId="ref22708" refString="Gozmany, L. (1978) Lecithoceridae. In: Amsel, H. G., Gregor, F. &amp; Reisser, H. (Eds.), Microlepidoptera Palaearctica. Band 5. Verlag Georg Fromme &amp; Co, Wien, pp. 1 - 306." type="book chapter" year="1978">Gozmány (1978)</bibRefCitation>
maintained it, provisionally, in the 
<taxonomicName box="[498,667,1791,1817]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="179" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Lecithoceridae</taxonomicName>
, suggesting however that it would probably be better placed in the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Meyrick" authorityYear="1890" box="[151,300,1827,1853]" class="Insecta" family="Xyloryctidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="179" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Xyloryctidae</taxonomicName>
, notably on account of its hind wing veins Rs and M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[881,889,1845,1859]" fontSize="6" pageId="28" pageNumber="179">1</subScript>
, which are not stalked (while normally stalked in 
<taxonomicName box="[151,323,1863,1890]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="179" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Lecithoceridae</taxonomicName>
). In fact, we propose here a close relationship of 
<taxonomicName authority="Meyrick" authorityName="Meyrick" authorityYear="1931" box="[879,1110,1863,1889]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" genus="Merocrates" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="179" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[879,1007,1863,1888]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="179">Merocrates</emphasis>
Meyrick
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Meyrick" authorityName="Meyrick" authorityYear="1906" box="[1166,1385,1863,1889]" class="Insecta" family="Oecophoridae" genus="Epichostis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="179" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1166,1283,1863,1889]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="179">Epichostis</emphasis>
Meyrick
</taxonomicName>
(the latter placed in “ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Meyrick" authorityYear="1890" box="[338,490,1899,1925]" class="Insecta" family="Xyloryctidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="179" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Xyloryctidae</taxonomicName>
” in, e.g., 
<bibRefCitation author="Clarke, J. F. G." box="[601,758,1898,1925]" pageId="28" pageNumber="179" refId="ref22504" refString="Clarke, J. F. G. (1955 b) Catalogue of the type specimens of Microlepidoptera in the British Museum (Natural History) described by Edward Meyrick. Vol. 2. Stenomidae, Xyloryctidae, Copromorphidae. Trustees of the British Museum, London, 531 pp." type="book" year="1955">Clarke 1955b</bibRefCitation>
), two genera having a similar hind wing venation, a similar forewing shape (somewhat truncate distally), and sharing two synapomorphies in the forewing venation, namely the complete fusion of R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[383,391,1989,2003]" fontSize="6" pageId="28" pageNumber="179">4</subScript>
and R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[462,470,1989,2003]" fontSize="6" pageId="28" pageNumber="179">5</subScript>
(i.e. the presence of only four visible R veins) and an arched vein CuA 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1250,1258,1989,2003]" fontSize="6" pageId="28" pageNumber="179">2</subScript>
that comes very close to the inner margin, being more or less parallel to it distally. Although the 
<typeStatus box="[1056,1154,2007,2033]" pageId="28" pageNumber="179">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName authority="Meyrick, 1931" authorityName="Meyrick" authorityYear="1931" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" genus="Merocrates" kingdom="Animalia" lastPageId="29" lastPageNumber="180" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="179" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="themelias">
<emphasis box="[1193,1436,2007,2033]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="179">Merocrates themelias</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Meyrick, E." box="[151,317,151,177]" pageId="29" pageNumber="180" pagination="33 - 64" refId="ref23699" refString="Meyrick, E. (1931) s. n. Exotic Microlepidoptera, 4 (2), 33 - 64." type="journal article" year="1931">Meyrick, 1931</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
has lost its abdomen and possesses, in the forewing, CuA veins that are distinctly stalked (
<bibRefCitation author="Clarke, J. F. G." pageId="29" pageNumber="180" refId="ref22557" refString="Clarke, J. F. G. (1965) Catalogue of the type specimens of Microlepidoptera in the British Museum (Natural History) described by Edward Meyrick. Vol. 5. Timyridae, Hyponomeutidae, Ethmiidae, Metachandidae, Cosmopterigidae, Walshiidae, Blastodacnidae, Scythridae. Trustees of the British Museum (Natural History), London, 581 pp." type="book" year="1965">Clarke, 1965: 178</bibRefCitation>
), we tentatively assign 
<emphasis box="[532,801,187,213]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="180">
“ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Herrich-Schaffer" authorityYear="1853" box="[543,687,187,213]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" genus="Lecithocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="180" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Lecithocera</taxonomicName>
” 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Park &amp; Koo &amp; Minet" authorityYear="2020" baseAuthorityName="Viette" baseAuthorityYear="1986" box="[705,801,187,213]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" genus="Merocrates" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="180" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ojejyella">ojejyella</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
to the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Meyrick" authorityYear="1931" box="[953,1081,187,212]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" genus="Merocrates" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="180" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[953,1081,187,212]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="180">Merocrates</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
on account of a synapomorphy in the forewing venation, viz. the stalked condition of R3 and R4+5. It should be noted that this Malagasy species had already been regarded as a close relative of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Lopez-Vaamonde et al., 2019: 113)" baseAuthorityName="Lopez-Vaamonde" baseAuthorityPageNumber="113" baseAuthorityYear="2019" box="[708,1252,259,285]" class="Insecta" family="Oecophoridae" genus="Epichostis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="180" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[708,825,259,285]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="180">Epichostis</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Lopez-Vaamonde, C. &amp; Sire, L. &amp; Rasmussen, B. &amp; Rougerie, R. &amp; Wieser, C. &amp; Allaoui, A. A. &amp; Minet, J. &amp; deWaard, J. R. &amp; Decaens, T. &amp; Lees, D. C." box="[842,1243,259,285]" pageId="29" pageNumber="180" pagination="108 - 121" refId="ref23330" refString="Lopez-Vaamonde, C., Sire, L., Rasmussen, B., Rougerie, R., Wieser, C., Allaoui, A. A., Minet, J., deWaard, J. R., Decaens, T. &amp; Lees, D. C. (2019) DNA barcodes reveal deeply neglected diversity and numerous invasions of micromoths in Madagascar. Genome, 62, 108 - 121. https: // doi. org / 10.1139 / gen- 2018 - 0065" type="journal article" year="2019">
Lopez-Vaamonde 
<emphasis box="[1050,1102,259,285]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="180">et al</emphasis>
., 2019: 113
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. This last genus was maintained in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Meyrick" authorityYear="1890" box="[368,514,295,321]" class="Insecta" family="Xyloryctidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="180" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Xyloryctidae</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Yuan, G. X. &amp; Wang, S. X." box="[559,804,295,321]" pageId="29" pageNumber="180" pagination="2141 - 2165" refId="ref25010" refString="Yuan, G. X. &amp; Wang, S. X. (2009) Checklist of the genus Epichostis Meyrick (Lepidoptera: Xyloryctidae) of the world, with descriptions of 11 new species from China. Journal of natural History, 43 (35 - 36), 2141 - 2165. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222930903034957" type="journal article" year="2009">Yuan &amp; Wang (2009)</bibRefCitation>
but was deliberately excluded from a recent, extensive molecular study of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stainton" authorityYear="1854" box="[414,562,331,357]" class="Insecta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="190" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="superFamily" superFamily="Gelechioidea">Gelechioidea</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Wang, Q. - Y. &amp; Li, H. - H." box="[577,779,331,357]" pageId="29" pageNumber="180" pagination="307 - 328" refId="ref24952" refString="Wang, Q. - Y. &amp; Li, H. - H. (2020) Phylogeny of the superfamily Gelechioidea (Lepidoptera: Obtectomera), with an exploratory application on geometric morphometrics. Zoologica Scripta, 49, 307 - 328. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / zsc. 12407" type="journal article" year="2020">Wang &amp; Li, 2020</bibRefCitation>
) because of its “highly unstable” position in phylogenetic trees. Moreover, unlike 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Meyrick" authorityYear="1890" box="[416,565,367,393]" class="Insecta" family="Xyloryctidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="180" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Xyloryctidae</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[576,693,367,393]" class="Insecta" family="Oecophoridae" genus="Epichostis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="180" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[576,693,367,393]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="180">Epichostis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
lacks spiniform scales (“spines”) on the abdomen and its forewing vein CuA 
<subScript attach="left" box="[260,268,421,435]" fontSize="6" pageId="29" pageNumber="180">2</subScript>
is markedly arched and, proximally, relatively close to CuA 
<subScript attach="left" box="[953,961,421,435]" fontSize="6" pageId="29" pageNumber="180">1</subScript>
(while CuA 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1102,1110,421,435]" fontSize="6" pageId="29" pageNumber="180">2</subScript>
is rather straight and remote from the base of CuA 
<quantity box="[393,430,439,471]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.54" pageId="29" pageNumber="180" unit="in" value="1.0">
<subScript attach="left" box="[393,401,457,471]" fontSize="6" pageId="29" pageNumber="180">1</subScript>
in
</quantity>
the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Meyrick" authorityYear="1890" box="[477,629,439,466]" class="Insecta" family="Xyloryctidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="180" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Xyloryctidae</taxonomicName>
). Therefore, pending further research work, the 
<taxonomicName box="[1162,1279,439,465]" class="Insecta" family="Oecophoridae" genus="Epichostis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="180" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1162,1279,439,465]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="180">Epichostis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
+ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Meyrick" authorityYear="1931" box="[1308,1436,439,464]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" genus="Merocrates" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="180" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1308,1436,439,464]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="180">Merocrates</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group must be considered 
<emphasis box="[447,601,475,501]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="180">incertae sedis</emphasis>
within the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stainton" authorityYear="1854" box="[728,879,475,501]" class="Insecta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="190" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="superFamily" superFamily="Gelechioidea">Gelechioidea</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
